04884nam a2200673Ia 9780300274967DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20232023ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803002749677 a10.12987/97803002749672doi  a(DE-B1597)666714  a(OCoLC)1393244370  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aJZ1253b.M43 2023 7aPOL0110002bisacsh04a327.10192231 aMearsheimer, John J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHow States Think :bThe Rationality of Foreign Policy /cSebastian Rosato, John J. Mearsheimer. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tChapter 1: The Rational Actor Assumption -- tChapter 2: Strategic Rationality and Uncertainty -- tChapter 3: Defining Strategic Rationality -- tChapter 4: Contending Definitions -- tChapter 5: Rationality and Grand Strategy -- tChapter 6: Rationality and Crisis Management -- tChapter 7: Nonrational State Behavior -- tChapter 8: Goal Rationality -- tChapter 9: Rationality in International Politics -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA groundbreaking examination of a central question in international relations: Do states act rationally? To understand world politics, you need to understand how states think. Are states rational? Much of international relations theory assumes that they are. But many scholars believe that political leaders rarely act rationally. The issue is crucial for both the study and practice of international politics, for only if states are rational can scholars and policymakers understand and predict their behavior. John J. Mearsheimer and Sebastian Rosato argue that rational decisions in international politics rest on credible theories about how the world works and emerge from deliberative decision-making processes. Using these criteria, they conclude that most states are rational most of the time, even if they are not always successful. Mearsheimer and Rosato make the case for their position, examining whether past and present world leaders, including George W. Bush and Vladimir Putin, have acted rationally in the context of momentous historical events, including both world wars, the Cold War, and the post–Cold War era. By examining this fundamental concept in a novel and comprehensive manner, Mearsheimer and Rosato show how leaders think, and how to make policy for dealing with other states.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aHeads of statexPsychology. 0aInternational relationsxDecision making. 0aInternational relationsxPsychological aspects. 0aOperational psychology. 0aRationalization (Psychology)xPolitical aspects. 0aRationalization (Psychology). 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aRosato, Sebastian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2023 Englishz978311131925408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Political Science 2023z9783111318677oZDB-23-PLW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074978640uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300274967?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300274967423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300274967/original  a978-3-11-074978-6  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 